Key ideas:
- Critical: evmVersion must be 'cancun' — older versions cause silent failures
- Add both testnet and mainnet to networks config for easy switching
- Foundry: set evm_version = 'cancun' in foundry.toml

0G Labs explicitly specifies in their documentation that contracts must be compiled with `evmVersion: 'cancun'`. This is one of the most common sources of confusion for new developers — missing this setting doesn't always cause an obvious error, but can lead to contracts that compile and deploy successfully yet fail at runtime.

**Hardhat configuration (`hardhat.config.js`):**
```javascript
require('@nomicfoundation/hardhat-toolbox');

module.exports = {
  solidity: {
    version: '0.8.19',
    settings: {
      evmVersion: 'cancun',  // CRITICAL: must be cancun
      optimizer: {
        enabled: true,
        runs: 200
      }
    }
  },
  networks: {
    testnet: {
      url: 'https://evmrpc-testnet.0g.ai',
      chainId: 16602,
      accounts: [process.env.PRIVATE_KEY]
    },
    mainnet: {
      url: 'https://evmrpc.0g.ai',
      chainId: 16661,
      accounts: [process.env.PRIVATE_KEY]
    }
  }
};
```

**Foundry configuration (`foundry.toml`):**
```toml
[profile.default]
evm_version = "cancun"

[rpc_endpoints]
0g_testnet = "https://evmrpc-testnet.0g.ai"
0g_mainnet = "https://evmrpc.0g.ai"
```

**Foundry deploy command:**
```bash
forge create --rpc-url https://evmrpc-testnet.0g.ai \
  --private-key $PRIVATE_KEY \
  --evm-version cancun \
  src/MyContract.sol:MyContract
```

**Remix**: Select 'cancun' from the EVM Version dropdown in the Solidity Compiler tab before compiling.

Key ideas:
- Fixed address: 0x0000000000000000000000000000000000001000
- Query DA quorum membership and epoch numbers from within smart contracts
- registerSigner() allows smart contracts to register new DA signers

0G Labs implemented the DASigners precompile as a native contract at a fixed address. Unlike regular smart contracts, precompiles run native Go code instead of EVM bytecode, making them extremely gas-efficient.

The DASigners precompile manages the registry of validators (signers) that participate in the DA consensus. Your smart contracts can query this registry to verify DA quorum membership without any external calls.

```solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.19;

interface IDASigners {
    struct Params {
        uint256 tokensPerVote;
        uint256 maxVotesPerSigner;
        uint256 maxQuorums;
        uint256 epochBlocks;
        uint256 encodedSlices;
    }

    function params() external view returns (Params memory);
    function epochNumber() external view returns (uint256);
    function getQuorum(uint256 epoch, uint256 quorumId) 
        external view returns (address[] memory);
}

contract DAVerifier {
    IDASigners constant DA_SIGNERS = 
        IDASigners(0x0000000000000000000000000000000000001000);

    function currentEpoch() external view returns (uint256) {
        return DA_SIGNERS.epochNumber();
    }

    function quorumMembers(uint256 epoch, uint256 quorumId)
        external view returns (address[] memory) {
        return DA_SIGNERS.getQuorum(epoch, quorumId);
    }
}
```

This enables powerful on-chain verification: your smart contract can confirm that a specific set of DA signers participated in a data availability attestation, creating fully on-chain DA proofs.

Key ideas:
- Fixed address: 0x0000000000000000000000000000000000001001
- Wraps native 0G into ERC20 W0G for DeFi protocol compatibility
- mint() and burn() use quota-based mechanism for controlled supply

0G Labs documented the WrappedOGBase precompile as the on-chain mechanism for wrapping the native 0G token into an ERC20-compatible W0G token.

Native tokens (like ETH on Ethereum) can't directly participate in ERC20-based DeFi protocols — you need a wrapped version that conforms to the ERC20 interface. This is why WETH exists on Ethereum. WrappedOGBase is 0G's equivalent.

```solidity
interface IWrappedOGBase {
    // Wrap native 0G into ERC20 W0G
    function mint(address minter, uint256 amount) external;

    // Unwrap W0G back to native 0G
    function burn(address minter, uint256 amount) external;
}

// Fixed address on all 0G networks
IWrappedOGBase constant WRAPPED_OG = 
    IWrappedOGBase(0x0000000000000000000000000000000000001001);
```

The quota-based minting mechanism prevents unconstrained token creation — only authorized contracts can call `mint()` within their allocated quota. This ensures the wrapped token supply accurately reflects the actual native token supply.

For developers building DeFi protocols, payment systems, or any application that needs to transfer 0G tokens between contracts using the ERC20 interface, this precompile is your entry point. For most application developers (Storage, Compute users), you won't need this directly — the SDK handles token management internally.
